<div id=ftn8>

<p class=MsoFootnoteText><a href="#_ftnref8" name="_ftn8" title=""><span
class=MsoFootnoteReference><span class=MsoFootnoteReference><span
style='font-size:13.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>[8]</span></span></span></a>
The poetess Corinna was added to the nine in some listings. <span
style='font-size:12.0pt;font-family:"Times New Roman","serif"'>Commentary of
Melampus or Diomedes on Dionysius of Thrace (p. 21, Hilgard), as quoted in
David A. Campbell, ed. and tr., <i>Greek Lyric, Volume IV: Bacchylides,
Corinna, and Others</i>, Loeb Classical Library (Cambridge MA: Harvard
University Press, 1992), 24-25. See also 18-23; Bekker, <i>Anecdota Graeca</i>,
2:751. Though Corinna continued to have a high reputation among Roman authors
and critics, there are major problems with the dating of her life and poetry.</span></p>

