<div id=ftn148>

<p class=MsoFootnoteText><a href="#_ftnref148" name="_ftn148" title=""><span
class=MsoFootnoteReference><span class=MsoFootnoteReference><span
style='font-size:13.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>[148]</span></span></span></a>
Haigh and Pickard-Cambridge, <i>The Attic Theatre</i>, 35.</p>

</div>

<div id=ftn149>

<p class=MsoFootnoteText><a href="#_ftnref149" name="_ftn149" title=""><span
class=MsoFootnoteReference><span class=MsoFootnoteReference><span
style='font-size:13.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>[149]</span></span></span></a>
Naboth Hedin, “Winning the Nobel Prize,” <i>Atlantic</i> (October 1950), at
http://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/1950/10/winning-the-nobel-prize/305480/.
Burton Feldman, <i>The Nobel Prize: A History of Genius, Controversy, and
Prestige</i> (NY: Arcade Pub., 2000), 69-70. Tolstoy was not even nominated in
1901, as the Permanent Secretary of the selection committee disagreed with his
political views. Later, Tolstoy unofficially let the Nobel organization know
that he would turn down the award if it was given to him.</p>

</div>

<div id=ftn150>

<p class=MsoFootnoteText><a href="#_ftnref150" name="_ftn150" title=""><span
class=MsoFootnoteReference><span class=MsoFootnoteReference><span
style='font-size:13.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>[150]</span></span></span></a>
Feldman, <i>The Nobel Prize</i>, 69.</p>

</div>

<div id=ftn151>

<p class=MsoFootnoteText><a href="#_ftnref151" name="_ftn151" title=""><span
class=MsoFootnoteReference><span class=MsoFootnoteReference><span
style='font-size:13.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>[151]</span></span></span></a>
Aulus Gellius, <i>Attic Nights</i>, 17.4.1, tr. Edmonds, p. 5. See also Haigh
and Pickard-Cambridge, <i>The Attic Theatre</i>, 35-36, listing cases in which
artistic judges were intimidated or bribed; Ioannis M. Konstantakos, “<i>Rara
coronato plausere theatra Menandro</i>? Menander's Success in His Lifetime,” <i>Quaderni
Urbinati di Cultura Classica</i>, New Series, 88.1 (2008): 79-106, especially
93. </p>

</div>

<div id=ftn152>

<p class=MsoFootnoteText><a href="#_ftnref152" name="_ftn152" title=""><span
class=MsoFootnoteReference><span class=MsoFootnoteReference><span
style='font-size:13.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>[152]</span></span></span></a>
Haigh and Pickard-Cambridge, <i>The Attic Theatre</i>, 37-38.</p>

</div>

<div id=ftn153>

<p class=MsoFootnoteText><a href="#_ftnref153" name="_ftn153" title=""><span
class=MsoFootnoteReference><span class=MsoFootnoteReference><span
style='font-size:13.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>[153]</span></span></span></a>
Plato, <i>Laws</i> 2.659A-C; 3.700C-701A: “in place of an aristocracy in music
there sprang up a kind of base theatrocracy.” Haigh and Pickard-Cambridge, <i>The
Attic Theatre</i>, 37-38.</p>

</div>

<div id=ftn154>

<p class=MsoFootnoteText><a href="#_ftnref154" name="_ftn154" title=""><span
class=MsoFootnoteReference><span class=MsoFootnoteReference><span
style='font-size:13.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>[154]</span></span></span></a>
As quoted in “The Storm Over the University,” <i>The New York Review of Books</i>,
December 6, 1990, available at http://www.ditext.com/searle/searle1.html
(accessed 5/17/15). </p>

</div>

<div id=ftn155>

<p class=MsoFootnoteText><a href="#_ftnref155" name="_ftn155" title=""><span
class=MsoFootnoteReference><span class=MsoFootnoteReference><span
style='font-size:13.0pt;font-family:"Garamond","serif"'>[155]</span></span></span></a>
